Copy constructor shallow copy vs deep copy.

class Number
{
public:
	int *n;
	
	Number(int set_n)
	{
		n = (int *) malloc(sizeof(int));
		*n = set_n;
	}
	
	
	~Number()
	{
		free(n);
	}
	
	int get()
	{
		return *n;
	}
};

int main()
{
 	Number numA(8);
 	cout << "numA: " << numA.get() << endl;
 	
 	Number numB = numA; //default copy constructor, performs a shallow copy
 	
 	cout << "numB: " << numB.get() << endl;
 	
 	*(numB.n) = 20; //this will also change the value of *(numA.n)
 	
 	//exit(0);
 	
 	return 0;   
}

SHALLOW COPY:
--------------------
numA uses dynamically allocated data, 

When Shallow copy occurs, the value of the member variables of numA 
	get assigned to the member variables of numB.
So in the case of pointer 'n', the memory address stored by numA 'n' 
	gets assigned to the memory address stored by numB 'n'. 

So both numA.n and numB.n are storing the same memory address. 
They are both pointing to the same value on the HEAP.

Memory space for integer 'n' was allocated once, when numA was created.
numB has the member variable 'n' set to the same memory address.

Say, numA (8);
numB = numA; //calling default Copy constructor performs shallow copy

If I print numA and numB, both will output 8. Which seems correct, but there is a problem.

1)
	Now this is going to be a problem.
	Say, 
	*(numB.n) = 20;
	If I print numA.n and numB.n , both will output 20. 
	But we only assigned 20 to member variable of numB.
2)
	Double free.
	The destructor will free numA followed by numB.
	Since numA member attribute and numB member attribute are pointing to the same memory location,
	numA will be freed first, no issue.
	When numB is freed, it is attempting to free memory location that has already been freed.

DEEP COPY of the object, when the constructor runs.
----------------------------
If I had a Copy constructor, it will perform a deep copy.

Number ( const Number& rhs)
{
		n = (int *)malloc(sizeof(int));
		*n = *(rhs.n); //deep copy , copying value of one object member to the other object member
}
